      "question": "What was the old async bridge, and how does JSI change the relationship between JS and native?",
      "answer": "The legacy bridge was an **asynchronous, batched message queue** between the JS and native realms. Calls and their arguments were serialized to JSON and shipped across in batches, so the two sides could never call each other synchronously and neither held a reference to the other's objects.\n\n`JSI` (JavaScript Interface) is a lightweight C++ layer that lets the JS engine hold **direct references to native objects** as `HostObject`s and call their methods synchronously, with no JSON serialization.\n\nThe nuance: JSI is engine-agnostic (it abstracts over Hermes, JSC, V8), and that synchronous, type-safe access is the foundation every other New Architecture piece (TurboModules, Fabric) is built on.\n\n**JSI is why New Architecture code calls native synchronously — no bridge, no JSON, no batching.**",
