      "question": "In the New Architecture, what do Fabric and TurboModules each replace, and what do they gain?",
      "answer": "Both are built on `JSI`.\n\n- **Fabric** is the new renderer. It replaces the old UIManager/async shadow-tree path with a C++ core that builds an immutable shadow tree and can commit synchronously, enabling things the old path couldn't — synchronous layout measurement and consistent reads via `useLayoutEffect`.\n- **TurboModules** replace the old NativeModules. Instead of eagerly initializing every module at startup and calling it over the bridge, they are **lazily loaded** and invoked synchronously through JSI.\n\nThe nuance: Fabric also lets React and native share one shadow tree across the render, commit, and mount phases, removing whole classes of out-of-order update bugs.\n\n**Fabric and TurboModules both trade eager, bridged access for lazy, synchronous JSI calls.**",
