      "question": "What does React's `key` prop do during reconciliation, and what breaks when you use the array index as the key?",
      "answer": "During reconciliation React diffs the new element tree against the previous one. Within a list, the `key` is the identity React uses to match an old child to a new child, so it can **reuse, reorder, or unmount** the existing component instance (fiber) instead of rebuilding it.\n\nUsing the array index ties identity to position, not to the data. When the list reorders, inserts at the front, or filters, the data shifts under stable indices, so React reuses the wrong instance.\n\nConcrete failures:\n\n- Local state (a `useState` value, a `TextInput`'s text, scroll position) sticks to the slot and attaches to the wrong item.\n- Lost animation/mount continuity, because items are updated in place rather than treated as moved.\n- In virtualized lists it also defeats cell reuse and can show stale rows.\n\n- Red flag: defaulting to the array index as key for any list that can reorder, filter, or insert — this is the single most common wrong answer to this question.\n\nUse a stable, data-derived id (`item.id`). Index keys are only safe for a static list that never reorders, inserts, or filters.\n\n**Key is identity, not position — always derive it from the data, never from where it sits in the array.**",
