      "answer": "**TTI** (time to interactive) is from launch to when the user can tap and get a response — not just first pixel. Cold start = native init, then load and execute the JS bundle, then the first React render and layout.\n\nWhat dominates: parsing and evaluating the JS bundle. With JSC the engine parses and compiles JS at startup, scaling with bundle size.\n\n**Hermes** ships **precompiled bytecode**: the bundle is compiled ahead of time, so startup skips the JS parse/compile step and just loads bytecode. That cuts TTI and memory, especially on low-end Android. Hermes is the default engine.\n\nSenior levers beyond Hermes: lazy-load heavy screens, defer non-critical work past first interaction, trim what runs before first render, and use **inline requires** (with RAM bundles where applicable) so modules evaluate on demand. Measure cold-start TTI with a real tool (`react-native-performance`, EAS Observe, or a native trace) — not a stopwatch, and exclude warm starts.\n\n**TTI is bounded by what runs before first render — Hermes cuts the parse/compile step, inline requires cut what still runs eagerly.**",
