      "answer": "A **worklet** is a JavaScript function marked (explicitly with `'worklet'` or implicitly inside hooks like `useAnimatedStyle`) that the Reanimated Babel plugin extracts so it can run on the **UI thread** in a separate JS runtime (the UI runtime), not the main JS thread.\n\nThis matters because the UI thread is the one that drives rendering. If your animation logic lives there, it can compute and commit each frame even while the JS thread is busy parsing JSON, running a heavy `useEffect`, or re-rendering a list.\n\nThe result is animations that hold 60/120fps independent of JS-thread load. The trade-off: a worklet captures its closure (shared values by reference, plain values by copy), and to call back into JS-thread code you need `runOnJS`.\n\n**A worklet runs on the UI thread by design — that's what lets animation logic survive a busy JS thread.**",
