      "answer": "Each `setState` triggers a full React cycle on the **JS thread**: render, reconcile, diff, commit, then the new props cross to native. Doing that every frame burns the ~16ms budget on JS work instead of painting (under the New Architecture the JS↔native hop is synchronous JSI rather than the old async bridge, but it's still JS-thread work).\n\nIf any frame's JS overruns, the UI thread has no fresh value to render and you drop a frame; under load (list rendering, network parsing) the animation stutters because it's coupled to JS-thread availability.\n\n- Red flag: driving a continuous value — a drag offset, a scroll position — through `setState` on every frame. It couples the animation to JS-thread availability, so any JS work (a render, a fetch) drops frames.\n\nThe fix is to **decouple animation from the render cycle**: shared values + `useAnimatedStyle` (Reanimated) or `useNativeDriver`/`Animated.event`, so values update directly on the UI thread.\n\n**State is for discrete UI React owns; continuous per-frame values should never round-trip through React.**",
