      "id": "rn-nav-2",
      "category": "navigation",
      "categoryLabel": "NAVIGATION",
      "question": "When would you reach for a Stack vs a Tabs navigator, and how do you nest them?",
      "answer": "Use a **Stack** for a push/pop flow where screens build on each other and you want a back gesture and header (list to detail). Use **Tabs** for parallel top-level sections the user switches between freely, where each tab keeps its own state.\n\nThe common pattern nests a Stack **inside** each tab so every tab has independent history: `app/(tabs)/_layout.tsx` renders `<Tabs>`, and each tab folder has its own `_layout.tsx` rendering `<Stack>`. A senior nuance: by default inactive tab screens stay **mounted** (they are not unmounted on blur), so use focus effects and `freezeOnBlur` to pause work rather than relying on unmount, and keep expensive setup out of module top level.\n\n**Stack for sequential drill-down, Tabs for parallel sections — nest a Stack inside each tab so every tab keeps its own history.**",
      "level": "mid"
