      "categoryLabel": "NAVIGATION",
      "question": "What are typed routes in expo-router and what do they buy you?",
      "answer": "Typed routes (`experiments.typedRoutes` in app config) make the dev server generate a `.d.ts` mapping of every route and its params from your `app/` tree. After that, `router.push`, `<Link href>`, and `useLocalSearchParams` are **statically typed**, so a path typo or a missing dynamic param is a TypeScript error instead of a runtime dead-end.\n\nThe practical win is refactor safety: rename or move a file and every navigation call to it fails to compile until fixed. The nuance is that the types are **generated**, so they can go stale until the dev server regenerates them, and an href built from a plain string escapes the checking unless you type it through the generated `Href` type.\n\n**Typed routes turn a renamed or moved file into a compile error at every call site, not a runtime dead end.**",
