      "question": "A tab screen stays mounted. How do you run logic only when it becomes visible vs hidden?",
      "answer": "Because tab screens stay mounted, `useEffect(..., [])` fires once at mount, not each time you return to the tab. For visibility-driven work use the focus lifecycle: `useFocusEffect(useCallback(() => { /* on focus */ return () => { /* on blur */ }; }, []))` runs on **focus** and cleans up on **blur**, every time.\n\nFor lighter needs, `useIsFocused()` returns a boolean to branch on, or subscribe via `navigation.addListener('focus' | 'blur', ...)`.\n\n- Red flag: relying on `useEffect(..., [])` to know when a tab becomes visible again — it fires once at mount, not on every return to the tab.\n\nA senior point: always wrap the `useFocusEffect` callback in `useCallback` or it re-subscribes on every render, and key off focus (not mount) to pause expensive things like video, polling, or location when a screen sits behind another tab.\n\n**Tab screens stay mounted — key visibility-driven work off focus/blur, not mount/unmount.**",
