      "category": "data",
      "categoryLabel": "STATE & DATA",
      "question": "One Context holds both rarely-changing config and frequently-changing UI state, and unrelated components keep re-rendering. Why, and how do you fix it?",
      "answer": "Every consumer of a Context re-renders whenever the **provider's `value` changes by reference**, no matter which field it actually reads. Context has no selector, so a fast-changing field drags slow consumers along with it.\n\nThe senior fix is to **split context by update frequency**, not by domain: stable data (theme, current user) in one provider, volatile data in another, so a config-only consumer never re-renders on a volatile change.\n\n- Red flag: treating Context as a general-purpose state manager — it has no selectors, so every consumer re-renders on any provider value change, no matter which field it actually reads.\n- Memoize `value` with `useMemo` so the provider doesn't hand out a fresh object every render.\n- Split state and dispatch into two contexts so action-only consumers don't re-render on state changes (`dispatch` is referentially stable).\n- When splitting isn't enough, use an external store (`useSyncExternalStore`, Zustand, Jotai) that supports **selector-based subscriptions**.\n\n**Split context by update frequency, not by domain — reach for a store with selectors once splitting isn't enough.**",
      "level": "mid"
