      "category": "data",
      "categoryLabel": "STATE & DATA",
      "question": "Explain stale-while-revalidate in React Query, and the role of `staleTime` versus `gcTime` (formerly `cacheTime`).",
      "answer": "**Stale-while-revalidate** means a query immediately returns cached data (even if stale) so the UI paints instantly, then refetches in the background and swaps in fresh data — you never block on the network for data you already have.\n\n- `staleTime` controls **when** data becomes stale. While fresh (within `staleTime`), React Query serves the cache and skips refetching on mount, focus, or reconnect. Default is `0`, so data is stale immediately.\n- `gcTime` (renamed from `cacheTime` in v5) controls **how long** an inactive query's data lingers after its last observer unmounts, before garbage collection. Default is 5 minutes.\n\nThe nuance: `staleTime` governs freshness/refetch decisions, `gcTime` governs retention. On mobile, raise `staleTime` to cut redundant refetches, since `focusManager` ties `refetchOnWindowFocus` to RN's `AppState`, which fires often.\n\n**staleTime decides whether to refetch; gcTime decides how long to keep the cache after nobody's watching.**",
      "level": "senior"
