      "category": "data",
      "categoryLabel": "STATE & DATA",
      "question": "Why must React state updates be immutable, and what's a concrete bug from mutating state directly?",
      "answer": "React decides whether to re-render via a **shallow reference comparison** (`Object.is`) of state and props. Mutate an object or array in place and the reference is unchanged, so React (and `memo`/`useMemo`/`useEffect` dependency arrays) sees \"no change\" and skips the update — the UI goes stale.\n\nA classic bug: `items.push(newItem); setItems(items)` passes the **same array reference**, so a memoized `FlatList` or child never re-renders. The fix produces a new reference: `setItems(prev => [...prev, newItem])`.\n\n- Use functional updates (`setX(prev => ...)`) to avoid stale-closure bugs in batched or async updates.\n- For deep/nested updates, reach for Immer (`produce`) to write \"mutative\" code that yields a new immutable tree — this is what Redux Toolkit uses under the hood.\n\n**React skips re-renders on same-reference state — mutate in place and the UI silently goes stale.**",
      "level": "junior"
