      "id": "rn-native-2",
      "category": "native",
      "categoryLabel": "NATIVE MODULES",
      "question": "Walk me through implementing a simple native module in Swift and Kotlin with the Expo Modules API.",
      "answer": "You write one class per platform that subclasses `Module` and returns a `ModuleDefinition` from its `definition()`.\n\n1. `Name(\"MyModule\")` sets the JS-visible name you later pass to `requireNativeModule`.\n2. `Function(\"add\") { (a: Int, b: Int) in a + b }` for a synchronous call on the JS thread; use `AsyncFunction` for work that should run off it or that resolves a `Promise`.\n3. `Property(\"version\") { ... }` for a getter; `Events(\"onChange\")` to declare events you fire with `sendEvent`.\n4. `Constants([...])` to expose static values read at init.\n\nSwift uses trailing closures and `throws`; Kotlin mirrors the same DSL with lambdas. On the TS side you wrap it with `requireNativeModule<MyModuleType>('MyModule')` so callers get a typed surface.\n\n**The definition block is the entire contract — name, functions, properties, and events, nothing hand-marshalled.**",
