      "question": "What are TurboModules and Codegen, and how do they change native modules under the New Architecture?",
      "answer": "TurboModules are the New Architecture replacement for legacy bridge native modules: they load lazily and are invoked directly over JSI instead of through the async, batched, JSON-serialized bridge, cutting startup cost and per-call latency.\n\nCodegen is the build-time tool that reads your TypeScript (or Flow) spec — a file named `Native<Name>` whose interface extends `TurboModule` and is exported via `TurboModuleRegistry.getEnforcing` — and emits the C++/Obj-C/Java interface glue, making the JS-to-native contract statically typed.\n\nThe senior nuance: the spec is the single source of truth, so Codegen runs during the build (`pod install` / Gradle) and a mismatch between spec and native implementation fails to compile rather than crashing at runtime. The Expo Modules API hides most of this, but knowing the flow matters when debugging third-party TurboModules.\n\n**Codegen makes the spec the single source of truth — a mismatch fails the build, not a user's runtime.**",
