      "question": "What is a config plugin, when do you need one, and why can't you just edit the native projects directly?",
      "answer": "A config plugin is a JavaScript function that mutates the generated native iOS/Android projects during `npx expo prebuild`, letting you apply native changes (Info.plist keys, AndroidManifest entries, Gradle/Podfile tweaks, entitlements) declaratively from your Expo config.\n\nYou need one under Continuous Native Generation, where `ios/` and `android/` are generated and usually not committed.\n\n- Red flag: hand-editing the generated `ios/`/`android/` projects directly — the next `prebuild` silently regenerates and overwrites the change, so it must live in a plugin to be reproducible.\n\nMechanically you compose mods like `withInfoPlist`, `withAndroidManifest`, and `withDangerousMod`; well-published modules ship their own plugin so consumers just add it to `plugins` in `app.json`. The nuance: prefer the typed mod helpers over `withDangerousMod`, which performs raw filesystem edits with no merge safety.\n\n**If it's not in a config plugin, the next prebuild will erase it.**",
