      "question": "Explain autolinking. How does Expo know to compile a native module without you touching Xcode or Gradle?",
      "answer": "Autolinking discovers native modules from your installed npm dependencies and wires them into the iOS and Android builds automatically, replacing the old manual `react-native link` step.\n\nReact Native core autolinking scans your dependency tree for packages that ship a native podspec/Gradle project (with `react-native.config.js` available to override or disable the defaults) and feeds them to CocoaPods and Gradle. Expo adds a layer on top: `expo-modules-autolinking` finds packages declaring an `expo-module.config.json` and registers their Swift/Kotlin modules with the generated `ModulesProvider` at build time.\n\nThe senior nuance: resolution happens at build time from the dependency graph, so you can exclude or override modules via the `expo.autolinking` config or RN's `dependencies` block, and a module that never appears is almost always a missing `expo-module.config.json` or a package the resolver couldn't see in a hoisted `node_modules`.\n\n**Autolinking replaces manual linking by discovering native modules from your dependency graph at build time.**",
