      "answer": "`jest-expo` ships a preset tuned to your Expo SDK: it sets `transformIgnorePatterns` so the untranspiled ESM/Flow/TS that Expo, React Native, and many community packages ship in `node_modules` actually gets run through Babel, it mocks Expo's native modules, and it can run one suite across `ios`, `android`, and `web` via `jest-expo/multi-project`.\n\nThe failure plain Jest hits first is `SyntaxError: Cannot use import statement outside a module`, because Jest ignores `node_modules` by default and those packages aren't pre-compiled. `jest-expo` already whitelists them.\n\nNuance: it pins a `react-test-renderer` and RN Jest preset compatible with your SDK.\n\n- Red flag: hand-installing your own `react-test-renderer` — `jest-expo` already bundles one pinned to your SDK, and version drift against it is a frequent source of cryptic errors.\n\n**jest-expo exists because plain Jest doesn't transpile the untranspiled ESM/Flow/TS that RN packages ship in node_modules.**",
