      "answer": "A native module has no JS implementation under Node, so you replace it with a test double. Common approaches:\n\n- `jest.mock('react-native-keychain', () => ({ setGenericPassword: jest.fn(), getGenericPassword: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue(false) }))` — module-level mock with controllable returns.\n- For Expo modules, rely on `jest-expo` (it mocks most) and override specifics with `jest.mock`.\n- If a library ships its own mock, register it once in a setup file referenced by `setupFiles` so every test gets it.\n\nNuance: match the real shape — if the API returns a Promise, the mock must too (`mockResolvedValue`) or `await` calls hang. For modules reached via `NativeModules.Foo`, mock that object rather than the JS wrapper, and `jest.clearAllMocks()` in `afterEach` so call counts don't leak between tests.\n\n**Mock the shape the real module returns — if it resolves a Promise, the mock must too, or awaits hang.**",
