      "question": "Maestro vs Detox for end-to-end testing — how do you choose, and what's the core trade-off?",
      "answer": "Both drive a real build on a simulator/emulator, but the philosophies differ:\n\n- **Maestro** is black-box: declarative YAML flows (`launchApp`, `tapOn`, `assertVisible`) that match by accessibility id or visible text, with built-in implicit waits and retries — so flows are less flaky and need almost no app instrumentation. Faster to author and maintain.\n- **Detox** is grey-box: it hooks the app's runtime to know when the JS thread is idle, giving deterministic synchronization, but you wire `testID`s carefully and own more setup.\n\nFor most RN/Expo teams Maestro wins on author speed and stability; Detox earns its keep when you need tight runtime sync or fine-grained control. Either way, stable `testID`/accessibility ids are the contract between app and flow.\n\nNuance: neither drives Expo Go — you need a dev-client or standalone build installed — and both slot into CI on EAS Workflows or GitHub Actions.\n\n**Maestro trades runtime control for authoring speed and stability; Detox trades setup cost for deterministic JS-thread sync.**",
