      "question": "On Hermes, how do you debug with React Native DevTools, and why doesn't the old Chrome 'Remote JS Debugging' apply?",
      "answer": "On Hermes you open **React Native DevTools** from the Dev Menu (`j` in the Metro terminal). It's a Chrome-DevTools-based frontend that connects to Hermes over the **Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP)** through Metro's inspector proxy, giving breakpoints, stepping, the console, and a CPU/memory profiler that run against the actual on-device JS engine.\n\n- Red flag: reaching for the legacy 'Remote JS Debugging' on Hermes — it ran your JS in Chrome's V8 in a separate process, which changed timing and broke synchronous native (JSI/TurboModule) calls. It's misleading on Hermes and now deprecated/removed for exactly that reason.\n\nDebugging in-engine means what you see matches production behavior.\n\nNuance: for perf work Hermes can emit a sampling profile you load into DevTools or Perfetto, and source maps must be wired up so stack traces and breakpoints map to your TypeScript rather than the bundled output.\n\n**Debug in the engine that ships to production — React Native DevTools talks to Hermes directly over CDP, no separate JS runtime in the loop.**",
